column1: Data Supplied By: National Livestock Reporting Service
Data source: National Livestock Reporting Service
Please see terms of use here: https://www.mla.com.au/general/Terms-and-conditions/data-and-information/

There were approximately 1,730 export and 400 young cattle penned representing a decrease of 770 head week-on-week. The regular buying group was present and joined by a couple of domestic processors in a cheaper market in places. Quality was very good in the trade and limited in the grown. Well finished trade cattle sold firm while secondary lots eased on some sales. Grown steers and bullocks sold firm to slightly dearer. Manufacturing steers held firm. Heavy grown heifers lifted 14c/kg. Cows sold 5c to 10c/kg cheaper across all grades. Heavy bulls lost 10c/kg. 

Vealers sold from 290c to 370c/kg. Yearling trade steers made between 315c and 380c/kg. Yearling heifers to the trade sold between 295c and 370c/kg. Grown steers made from 334c to 360c/kg. Bullocks sold from 334c to 366c/kg. Heavy grown heifers with finish made between 320c and 350c/kg. 

Heavy Friesian manufacturing steers sold between 272c and 320c with the crossbred portion between 278c and 350c/kg. Most light and medium weight cows made from 200c to 270c/kg. Heavy weight cows sold mostly from 240c to 304c/kg. Heavy bulls made between 230c and 280c/kg. 

Market reporter: Brendan Fletcher.
